<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Mortonia</i> <i>utahensis</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Agave</i> <i>utahensis</i>, <i>Echinocactus</i> <i>polycephalus</i>, <i>Echinocereus</i> <i>engelmannii</i>, <i>Eriogonum</i> <i>heermannii</i>, <i>Ferocactus</i> <i>cylindraceus</i>, <i>Gutierrezia</i> <i>sarothrae</i>, <i>Opuntia</i> <i>basilaris</i>, <i>Purshia</i> <i>stansburiana</i> and <i>Thamnosma</i> <i>montana</i>. Lichen and cryptogamic crust are also often present . </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 3 m; canopy is open. Herbaceous layer is sparse to open. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Mortonia utahensis</i> > 50% relative cover or is codominant with shrubs such as <i>Agave utahensis </i>in the shrub canopy (Evens et al. 2014).</li>
		
		<li><i>Mortonia utahensis</i> â‰¥ 2% cover in the shrub canopy; no other species with greater or equal cover (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Open moderate to steep slopes and cliffs at mid-elevations. Soils are well drained, shallow, bedrock or rocky, rapidly permeable, and usually calcareous.  </div>
</div>

        
